reflection_text: I don't really know enough to know whether this is something I should oppose or support. The species obviously does well here, but does it do so well that it is actively damaging the environment or just changing it? Culling a species that is invasive is understandable if it would lead to some ecological collapse, or endanger human populations. Will these other wild species be driven to extinction or just lower numbers? What kind of plan is in place for the culling and what will the costs be both economic and environmental? I'm not only not sure if it's the right plan of action, I'm not sure exactly what the plan is. I don't feel comfortable supporting issues that are vague.
griz_comments: I would be concerned with how the landscape would need to be altered to reintroduce a species that has not been extant in these lands for a hundred years. At that point, is it any different than whomever introduced the wild boar? On the first issue you're discussing a program to cull a species that is here and thriving and in another, reintroducing a species that did not survive culling a century ago. Where is the common sense?

support_letter: I support hunting these pigs, capturing them and slaughtering them for food or for household goods. Each pig can be eaten and made into sausage, pork chops, rump roast, pig feet dishes and bacon. Bacon is so popular these days. There is even a festival dedicated to Guy Ferrari's bacon in Modesto or Manteca, I forgot where exactly this Bacon Fest took place but there were advertisementsfor it on Facebook. Everyone loves bacon! So why not Wild Boar Bacon? Beer Basted Pork Ribs are another thing that people love. Barbeque's are very popular . Their head can be used to make head cheese. Their intestines can be used for casings for the sausages. Their heads could even be mounted on walls to make home decor. Boar bristle brushes for barbeque grills can be harvested. You could even make jewelry out of the tusks. the skin can be used for leather. There ARE lots of things that can be done with a wild boar other than just food sources.

It was their wild instinct to migrate out because they do not have a food source here in California to live and breed. Introducing them back would confuse and destroy them. They will forage for food in trash cans and people's homes. They need fish and berries to live and eat and this IS NOT in California for them anymore. They also may not like the temperature in the state anymore. It may be too warm or too cold depending. And they do not have a place to hibrernate like a bear should. DO NOT selfishly force them to live in a climate they do not wish to be in. Animals are not stupid. They know when to migrate.

They've left or migrated for survival they are not unhappy.  People treat dogs like humans and dogs do not think like humans. oppose_letter: I am concerned that this plan has not been thought through thoroughly. As it has been so long since wild pigs were first introduced here, they have probably adapted to serve a purpose in California's environment. I think it is prudent to examine their role in California before trying to eliminate them from the area entirely. I am hesitant to say this because invasive species often have a negative effect on native flora and fawna but I don't think we should do anything rash without further research. Yes, something should be done to control the population but I want to have more information before we get rid of them entirely. We also shouldn't demonize them before examining their role due to how people in rural areas in Northern California have needlessly threatened to kill the wolves which keep trying to come here from Oregon.

oppose_letter: I understand that wild pigs are causing disruption across the state, but to eliminate entirely does not sound like a great solution. I do not have a perfect answer to calm both sides of this topic, but to me at least, wild pigs have just as much right to roam our state as does any other animal. Perhaps a capture and release program could be put in place to move them to other areas of the country where their behaviors may not be such a problem for its residents.
